WEBVTT

1
00:00:08.218 --> 00:00:10.554
- You told them about the money?
- I did what I had to do.

2
00:00:10.637 --> 00:00:11.972
You didn't leave me a choice!

3
00:00:12.055 --> 00:00:14.892
You had a choice. to do what I told you
to do and leave it alone.

4
00:00:14.975 --> 00:00:16.894
I don't take my orders from you.

5
00:00:16.977 --> 00:00:19.605
You have no idea how much worse
you've made this. Hutton.

6
00:00:20.606 --> 00:00:22.274
Is that some sort of threat?

7
00:00:27.821 --> 00:00:28.739
I'm hit!

8
00:00:28.740 --> 00:00:30.450
- Oh. God! I'm hit!
- Hold on!

9
00:00:40.334 --> 00:00:41.292
Get us out of here!

10
00:00:41.293 --> 00:00:43.795
Minesweep. This is Minesweep One.
We are under attack.

11
00:00:43.879 --> 00:00:47.382
Three clicks north of Al-Jahra.
Hutton. get down!

12
00:00:47.466 --> 00:00:51.470
This is Minesweeper One.
Lieutenant Harold Cooper. We are under fire.

13
00:00:51.553 --> 00:00:56.016
Repeat. Lieutenant Harold Cooper.
Minesweeper One. We are under attack.

14
00:00:56.099 --> 00:00:57.851
Hang on. Hutton. Hold on.

15
00:01:10.322 --> 00:01:13.283
Well. what do you think? Great. right?

16
00:01:13.367 --> 00:01:14.701
She has a lot of experience.

17
00:01:15.702 --> 00:01:18.163
Yeah. All her references raved about her.

18
00:01:18.247 --> 00:01:22.167
We're meeting this afternoon.
but I have a good feeling about her.

19
00:01:22.251 --> 00:01:24.211
Looks like you found yourself a nanny.

20
00:01:24.294 --> 00:01:28.966
Which is a huge relief. I mean.
it's impossible to find someone great.

21
00:01:29.049 --> 00:01:30.342
I wouldn't know.

22
00:01:31.510 --> 00:01:34.179
Have you reached out to her yet.
to your daughter?

23
00:01:34.263 --> 00:01:36.098
I haven't worked up the courage yet.

24
00:01:36.181 --> 00:01:37.641
You should just do it.

25
00:01:37.724 --> 00:01:39.935
I put her through some dark times.

26
00:01:41.728 --> 00:01:45.232
Have you noticed the men
parked across the street every day?

27
00:01:45.315 --> 00:01:46.483
Every night?

28
00:01:46.566 --> 00:01:48.735
I thought so. but I wasn't sure.

29
00:01:48.819 --> 00:01:51.571
They're there for my protection.

30
00:01:51.655 --> 00:01:53.365
Yours? Why?

31
00:01:53.448 --> 00:01:54.866
Who do you need protection from?

32
00:01:54.950 --> 00:01:57.786
- My mother.
- No. That can't be true.

33
00:01:57.869 --> 00:02:00.998
Trust me. whatever pushed you
and your daughter apart.

34
00:02:01.081 --> 00:02:04.293
it's nothing compared to what
me and my mother have gone through.

35
00:02:04.376 --> 00:02:07.921
Just call her. I'm sure she'd appreciate it.

36
00:02:08.005 --> 00:02:11.842
- Would you. if your mother called you?
- It doesn't matter. She's not going to.

37
00:02:11.925 --> 00:02:13.719
- But if she did.
- She won't.

38
00:02:13.802 --> 00:02:15.345
My mother isn't like you.

39
00:02:15.429 --> 00:02:17.973
You want a relationship with your daughter.

40
00:02:19.099 --> 00:02:20.099
She doesn't.

41
00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:30.694
Hey. What's going on?

42
00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:36.366
We've done great work. Important work.

43
00:02:37.701 --> 00:02:38.952
Work we can be proud of.

44
00:02:39.036 --> 00:02:41.538
I think so too.

45
00:02:41.621 --> 00:02:44.916
I've made up my mind
about Reddington's true identity.

46
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:46.835
I'm going to tell Main Justice.

47
00:02:46.918 --> 00:02:48.587
And risk having them shut us down?

48
00:02:48.670 --> 00:02:52.382
As I say. we've done great work.

49
00:02:52.466 --> 00:02:54.217
Does it really matter who he is?

50
00:02:54.301 --> 00:02:57.679
- To the job we're doing. I mean.
- Not to me.

51
00:02:57.763 --> 00:02:59.598
It will to them.

52
00:02:59.681 --> 00:03:03.769
- Was there something you wanted?
- Yeah. I wanted this afternoon off.

53
00:03:03.852 --> 00:03:07.731
I found a nanny. Well. I think I did.
I'm meeting with her this afternoon.

54
00:03:07.814 --> 00:03:10.525
I told you before.
take whatever time you need.

55
00:03:10.609 --> 00:03:12.235
About Reddington...

56
00:03:12.319 --> 00:03:14.529
- You've already reached out to Main Justice?
- Yes.

57
00:03:14.613 --> 00:03:18.658
- I've set a meeting with Cynthia Panabaker.
- Sir.

58
00:03:18.742 --> 00:03:22.871
This just came in over SIPRNet.
Odd. right?

59
00:03:22.954 --> 00:03:24.414
What's odd about it?

60
00:03:24.498 --> 00:03:27.626
It was sent from an unofficial CIA outpost
in Zahedan.

61
00:03:30.253 --> 00:03:31.671
You're sure this is correct?

62
00:03:31.755 --> 00:03:34.174
- I decoded it myself.
- I need verification.

63
00:03:34.257 --> 00:03:36.968
Fingerprints. dog tags. a photo.
whatever they can send us.

64
00:03:37.052 --> 00:03:39.805
Yes. sir. But who is Daniel Hutton?

65
00:03:41.848 --> 00:03:43.558
A man who died 30 years ago.

66
00:04:03.412 --> 00:04:05.247
Visiting old ghosts?

67
00:04:07.207 --> 00:04:11.962
I received some news today.
Daniel Hutton is alive.

68
00:04:12.045 --> 00:04:14.131
Well. that's not possible.

69
00:04:14.214 --> 00:04:18.051
He walked out of the mountains
of southern Iran yesterday.

70
00:04:18.135 --> 00:04:20.512
<i>Found his way to a classified CIA outpost.</i>

71
00:04:20.595 --> 00:04:22.514
Daniel Hutton is dead. Harold.

72
00:04:22.597 --> 00:04:24.599
- We both know that.
- Do we?

73
00:04:24.683 --> 00:04:27.602
<i>Because it seems he's risen
like Lazarus from the grave.</i>

74
00:04:27.686 --> 00:04:30.856
<i>Hutton is reporting he's been kept prisoner
at multiple locations</i>

75
00:04:30.939 --> 00:04:32.858
in the Middle East since 1989.

76
00:04:32.941 --> 00:04:35.735
He escaped from captivity a week ago.
Asked for me by name.

77
00:04:35.819 --> 00:04:40.449
CIA assets in Iran reached out directly.
They don't want anything to do with this.

78
00:04:40.532 --> 00:04:42.742
He's asking for my help
to get out of the country.

79
00:04:42.826 --> 00:04:46.079
or his captors
will hunt him down and kill him.

80
00:04:46.163 --> 00:04:49.332
- Did you know? All this time?
- Did I know what?

81
00:04:49.416 --> 00:04:51.001
That he's alive?

82
00:04:52.419 --> 00:04:53.837
While you held this over my head.

83
00:04:55.255 --> 00:05:00.135
I gave you that so you could put
the whole incident behind you.

84
00:05:00.218 --> 00:05:04.723
<i>not carry it like an albatross
around your neck.</i>

85
00:05:04.806 --> 00:05:07.934
<i>I believed. as you believed.
that the man was dead.</i>

86
00:05:08.018 --> 00:05:12.856
<i>and that the issue of what happened
in Kuwait was resolved.</i>

87
00:05:12.939 --> 00:05:17.152
<i>I won't look the other way again.
I carried this secret for way too long.</i>

88
00:05:17.235 --> 00:05:18.737
I have to do something.

89
00:05:18.820 --> 00:05:21.364
I suggest the utmost discretion.

90
00:05:21.448 --> 00:05:24.493
to preserve flexibility.

91
00:05:24.576 --> 00:05:25.869
What do you mean. flexibility?

92
00:05:25.952 --> 00:05:30.123
It's Iran. Harold.
We can't just stroll through the front door.

93
00:05:30.207 --> 00:05:33.668
We don't know what we're walking into.
So we keep it small.

94
00:05:33.752 --> 00:05:36.880
No team. Just you and I.

95
00:05:36.963 --> 00:05:39.883
Until you look this man in the eye.

96
00:05:39.966 --> 00:05:44.137
until you know for sure what you plan to do.

97
00:05:45.263 --> 00:05:49.226
- I plan to do the right thing.
- We'll soon find out. won't we?

98
00:05:58.818 --> 00:06:00.111
<i>It happened fast.</i>

99
00:06:00.195 --> 00:06:03.865
<i>I remember Lieutenant Hutton getting hit.
I remember radioing and returning fire.</i>

100
00:06:03.949 --> 00:06:05.659
<i>But they were everywhere.</i>

101
00:06:05.742 --> 00:06:08.703
<i>I tried to keep him safe.
but next thing I knew...</i>

102
00:06:10.247 --> 00:06:11.373
<i>they had taken him.</i>

103
00:06:12.666 --> 00:06:14.292
<i>He was gone.</i>

104
00:06:14.376 --> 00:06:17.212
Your actions were commendable.
Lieutenant Cooper.

105
00:06:17.295 --> 00:06:20.215
but I have to ask you about reports
that you and Lieutenant Hutton

106
00:06:20.298 --> 00:06:23.009
were seen arguing prior to these events.

107
00:06:24.261 --> 00:06:26.346
- That never happened.
- What never happened?

108
00:06:26.429 --> 00:06:29.307
<i>That you had words
or that they were argumentative?</i>

109
00:06:42.112 --> 00:06:44.656
- What are you doing?
- These are supposed to be med supplies.

110
00:06:44.739 --> 00:06:46.408
- Close the crate.
- Where's this going?

111
00:06:46.491 --> 00:06:48.076
Who are you funding? Is it the Kurds?

112
00:06:48.159 --> 00:06:50.203
You're smuggling cash
to Iraq to fund rebels?

113
00:06:50.287 --> 00:06:52.914
- I said. close the crate.
- We're here to stabilise this region.

114
00:06:52.998 --> 00:06:54.874
not bankroll some private. dirty little war.

115
00:06:54.958 --> 00:06:57.127
Dan. I'm warning you. just close the crate.

116
00:07:04.551 --> 00:07:08.138
I forgot how handsome you were
back then. Harold.

117
00:07:08.221 --> 00:07:10.849
And how loosely tethered to the facts.

118
00:07:10.932 --> 00:07:12.934
You're one to talk about facts.

119
00:07:13.018 --> 00:07:16.187
Aren't you. Mr Koslov?

120
00:07:16.271 --> 00:07:18.815
So Elizabeth finally told you.

121
00:07:18.898 --> 00:07:20.817
She took longer than I thought she would.

122
00:07:20.900 --> 00:07:24.863
Once word was out.
I figured I was on borrowed time.

123
00:07:24.946 --> 00:07:27.490
And I'm sure. knowing you as I do.

124
00:07:27.574 --> 00:07:31.828
that you'll feel an obligation
to report this to the powers that be.

125
00:07:31.911 --> 00:07:33.163
I don't see a way around it.

126
00:07:33.246 --> 00:07:37.000
If you do that.
they'll take the task force away from you.

127
00:07:37.083 --> 00:07:41.171
- It'll be the end of what you've built.
- I'm sorry. It's my duty.

128
00:07:44.507 --> 00:07:47.093
Well. we're not finished just yet. are we?

129
00:07:47.177 --> 00:07:49.387
You must admit. though. it's ironic.

130
00:07:49.471 --> 00:07:54.684
Us jetting over there to protect your secret
and you refusing to protect mine.

131
00:07:54.768 --> 00:07:57.896
We're not protecting anything.
We're righting what was wrong.

132
00:07:59.189 --> 00:08:00.899
Keep telling yourself that.

133
00:08:02.484 --> 00:08:06.071
How do you even know about Hutton?
The real Reddington was there.

134
00:08:06.154 --> 00:08:09.115
<i>He was part of an oversight panel
and testified about it later.</i>

135
00:08:09.199 --> 00:08:10.950
<i>but you're not him.</i>

136
00:08:11.034 --> 00:08:13.953
How do you know anything about it
if you weren't there?

137
00:08:14.037 --> 00:08:15.747
I know because...

138
00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:19.793
I know.

139
00:08:19.918 --> 00:08:22.921
Because whoever I once was. I am now.

140
00:08:23.004 --> 00:08:27.300
and will continue to be. Raymond Reddington.

141
00:08:27.384 --> 00:08:31.763
Given where we're going.
the real question is. who are you?

142
00:08:31.846 --> 00:08:36.267
Are you the man in front of me.
who I know to be good and decent?

143
00:08:36.351 --> 00:08:38.228
Or are you the man from years ago

144
00:08:38.311 --> 00:08:42.399
who got himself into this mess
in the first place?

145
00:08:43.566 --> 00:08:47.237
We'll be arriving shortly.
Farhad will meet us at the airstrip.

146
00:08:48.363 --> 00:08:50.365
Do you think Hutton knows?

147
00:08:50.448 --> 00:08:54.244
Do you think he has any idea what part
you played in what happened back then?

148
00:08:54.327 --> 00:08:57.997
I don't think so.
Otherwise. he wouldn't have asked for me.

149
00:08:58.081 --> 00:08:59.290
Let's hope not.

150
00:08:59.374 --> 00:09:04.504
Because if he does hold you responsible
and if he plans to tell the world.

151
00:09:04.587 --> 00:09:06.423
then we'll have to shut him up.

152
00:09:06.506 --> 00:09:08.550
- I'm not gonna do that.
- No. I know.

153
00:09:11.094 --> 00:09:12.762
I guess that's why I'm here.

154
00:09:16.766 --> 00:09:19.394
- I can work pretty crazy hours.
- Oh. that's fine.

155
00:09:19.477 --> 00:09:20.603
Some weekends.

156
00:09:20.687 --> 00:09:23.273
- Some travelling.
- Honestly. whatever you need.

157
00:09:23.356 --> 00:09:27.068
If it helps. I can stay here when
you're gone so Agnes can keep her routine.

158
00:09:27.152 --> 00:09:28.653
I spoke to some of your references.

159
00:09:28.737 --> 00:09:31.406
<i>Is it true that
you watched their kids and cooked?</i>

160
00:09:31.489 --> 00:09:32.949
<i>Yes. I love to cook.</i>

161
00:09:33.032 --> 00:09:34.701
<i>Oh. good. Because on my best day.</i>

162
00:09:34.784 --> 00:09:38.204
<i>the best I can do is peanut butter
and jelly and tuna fish.</i>

163
00:09:38.288 --> 00:09:39.204
<i>You're busy.</i>

164
00:09:39.205 --> 00:09:41.750
<i>Myjob is to put time into areas you can't.</i>

165
00:09:41.833 --> 00:09:45.545
<i>You have no idea how much I need that.
How much Agnes needs it.</i>

166
00:09:45.628 --> 00:09:47.380
I'd be lucky to do it.

167
00:09:47.464 --> 00:09:49.591
Great. When can you start?

168
00:09:52.343 --> 00:09:55.221
Farhad! You son of a cur.

169
00:09:55.305 --> 00:09:57.432
It's been an awfully long time.

170
00:09:58.892 --> 00:10:01.394
You look good. my friend. And prosperous.

171
00:10:01.478 --> 00:10:03.605
May Khodah in his infinite wisdom

172
00:10:03.688 --> 00:10:06.858
keep the sanctions in place
for as long as possible.

173
00:10:06.941 --> 00:10:08.359
Of course you remember Dembe.

174
00:10:08.443 --> 00:10:11.321
This is the associate of mine
we spoke about.

175
00:10:11.404 --> 00:10:13.239
You violated sanctions on Iran?

176
00:10:13.323 --> 00:10:17.827
Sanctions have caused a certain amount
of investment in Iran to dry up.

177
00:10:17.911 --> 00:10:19.037
It's a barren garden.

178
00:10:19.120 --> 00:10:22.415
- I decided to water it.
- At a healthy interest rate.

179
00:10:22.499 --> 00:10:24.501
It's all the rage.

180
00:10:24.584 --> 00:10:27.504
Despite my associate's
reflexive flag-waving.

181
00:10:27.587 --> 00:10:33.092
he's a fine man in need of careful guidance
in and out of this CIA outpost

182
00:10:33.176 --> 00:10:35.178
everyone pretends to know nothing about.

183
00:10:35.261 --> 00:10:37.806
I've made the arrangements as discussed.

184
00:10:37.889 --> 00:10:41.017
One of my best men to drive you
and a backup vehicle for protection.

185
00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:44.187
This close to the border.
there are checkpoints all over the place.

186
00:10:44.270 --> 00:10:45.605
They can be tricky.

187
00:10:45.688 --> 00:10:49.567
Fortunately. the right bribes can get a man
where he needs to go.

188
00:10:49.651 --> 00:10:52.695
I'll have a double Scotch waiting for you
when you get back.

189
00:10:52.779 --> 00:10:54.072
You're not coming?

190
00:10:54.155 --> 00:10:57.242
I've made a lot of trouble in Iran
through the years.

191
00:10:57.325 --> 00:11:00.161
Best not to have a sore thumb sticking out.

192
00:11:05.124 --> 00:11:07.377
When we get to the checkpoint. don't speak.

193
00:11:07.460 --> 00:11:10.255
Don't draw attention.
Just look out the windshield at the view.

194
00:11:10.338 --> 00:11:12.423
They'll forget me the moment they see me.

195
00:11:43.705 --> 00:11:46.833
These dog tags
were the only thing he had on him.

196
00:11:46.916 --> 00:11:48.710
- You have a release?
- You kidding?

197
00:11:48.793 --> 00:11:50.628
We don't exist.

198
00:11:50.712 --> 00:11:52.171
We didn't invite this guy here.

199
00:11:52.255 --> 00:11:55.258
and we sure as hell
don't want him found here.

200
00:11:56.301 --> 00:11:57.802
He's your problem now.

201
00:12:10.815 --> 00:12:11.815
Hutton?

202
00:12:15.820 --> 00:12:18.907
Harold? Hey. is it really you?

203
00:12:20.366 --> 00:12:21.951
It's me. Dan.

204
00:12:29.250 --> 00:12:31.669
I've dreamt of this moment so many times.

205
00:12:32.921 --> 00:12:36.674
I can't believe I'm looking at you.
I went to your funeral.

206
00:12:38.009 --> 00:12:39.344
How did you survive?

207
00:12:42.847 --> 00:12:43.847
I don't know.

208
00:12:45.767 --> 00:12:47.769
They tortured me for...

209
00:12:48.895 --> 00:12:50.021
I don't know how long.

210
00:12:52.106 --> 00:12:56.444
Traded me. sold me for intel.
different factions.

211
00:12:57.779 --> 00:13:01.157
Do you remember anyone who had you?
Even for a short time?

212
00:13:03.952 --> 00:13:05.328
There was an Iranian.

213
00:13:07.080 --> 00:13:08.706
They called him the Simoon.

214
00:13:08.790 --> 00:13:11.125
Everyone in the intelligence community
has heard of him.

215
00:13:11.209 --> 00:13:13.878
He's been a dangerous intel leak
in the Middle East for years.

216
00:13:13.962 --> 00:13:16.005
Name means "poison wind."

217
00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:19.175
Everywhere he goes. people die.

218
00:13:19.258 --> 00:13:23.680
The intel he's given to terrorist cells
has led to armed embassy raids in Pakistan.

219
00:13:23.763 --> 00:13:29.185
a consulate bombing in Syria.
the death of countless U.S. citizens.

220
00:13:29.268 --> 00:13:31.479
Dan. it's a miracle you're alive.

221
00:13:33.189 --> 00:13:35.358
It's a miracle we're both alive.

222
00:13:37.193 --> 00:13:39.153
I remember that day in Kuwait.

223
00:13:41.823 --> 00:13:43.324
How did you survive that?

224
00:13:45.743 --> 00:13:46.786
I'm not sure.

225
00:13:47.912 --> 00:13:49.372
But you did. thank God.

226
00:13:54.085 --> 00:13:56.546
Harold. the last time I saw you...

227
00:13:58.297 --> 00:14:00.216
I want to apologise.

228
00:14:00.299 --> 00:14:01.718
That's behind us now.

229
00:14:02.844 --> 00:14:03.928
I was young.

230
00:14:07.473 --> 00:14:10.810
- What you saw was none of your business.
- It's too late. I went to the captain.

231
00:14:10.893 --> 00:14:13.479
I won't be an accomplice
to whatever you're involved with.

232
00:14:13.563 --> 00:14:14.689
Told him everything I saw.

233
00:14:14.772 --> 00:14:16.733
- Told him about the money?
- Did what I had to.

234
00:14:16.816 --> 00:14:20.069
- You didn't leave me a choice!
- You had a choice. do what I told you to do.

235
00:14:20.153 --> 00:14:22.238
- Leave it alone.
- I don't take my orders from you.

236
00:14:22.321 --> 00:14:24.490
You have no idea how much worse
you've made this.

237
00:14:24.574 --> 00:14:26.284
Is that some sort of threat?

238
00:14:29.412 --> 00:14:31.664
- I'm hit! Oh. God! I'm hit!
- Hold on!

239
00:14:33.791 --> 00:14:35.960
It all seems so unimportant now.

240
00:14:37.920 --> 00:14:41.007
But I knew. sitting in captivity.
despite what I did...

241
00:14:42.175 --> 00:14:45.136
that you would come back for me.
You would never abandon me.

242
00:14:46.971 --> 00:14:48.473
Because you're honourable.

243
00:14:50.058 --> 00:14:51.601
That's what sustained me.

244
00:14:53.561 --> 00:14:55.855
That if Harold Cooper
survived that firefight.

245
00:14:55.938 --> 00:14:57.982
he would come back for me. no matter what.

246
00:14:59.150 --> 00:15:02.695
Minesweep. This is Minesweep One.
We are under attack. Heavy fire.

247
00:15:02.779 --> 00:15:06.199
This is Lieutenant Harold Cooper.
Minesweeper One. We are under attack.

248
00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:16.793
So when I finally escaped
and I knew enough to get myself here.

249
00:15:16.876 --> 00:15:21.506
I also knew there was only one person
that I could reach out to.

250
00:15:21.589 --> 00:15:26.010
one person who would stop at nothing
to get me the rest of the way home.

251
00:15:27.845 --> 00:15:32.225
And here you are to rescue me.

252
00:15:32.308 --> 00:15:36.479
Dan. I'm gonna get you home.

253
00:15:41.150 --> 00:15:42.610
Thank you. my friend.

254
00:15:43.945 --> 00:15:44.945
Thank you.

255
00:15:57.333 --> 00:15:58.876
I taste a bit of allspice.

256
00:15:58.960 --> 00:16:02.922
You're right. for arthritis and libido.

257
00:16:07.468 --> 00:16:08.928
Whoever your friend's package is.

258
00:16:09.011 --> 00:16:11.347
I assume the outpost
wants to get rid of him.

259
00:16:11.430 --> 00:16:12.974
I would assume as much.

260
00:16:13.057 --> 00:16:16.018
But I'm sure the Revolutionary Guard
would like to have him.

261
00:16:16.102 --> 00:16:17.687
They'll find him sooner or later.

262
00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:19.939
Time. for now. is on our side.

263
00:16:22.692 --> 00:16:25.111
I think we may have a situation.

264
00:16:25.194 --> 00:16:26.863
- Have you heard from Harold?
- No.

265
00:16:26.946 --> 00:16:30.324
But our scouts say the route
between him and the airstrip

266
00:16:30.408 --> 00:16:32.076
is suddenly swarming with patrols.

267
00:16:33.870 --> 00:16:36.414
- Trouble?
- How many extra men can you bring?

268
00:16:36.497 --> 00:16:39.834
I'm paying 3000 a man now. I'll double it.

269
00:16:39.917 --> 00:16:42.753
- I need men who can shoot straight.
- I'll make the call.

270
00:16:47.633 --> 00:16:49.093
Harold. Are you on your way?

271
00:16:49.177 --> 00:16:52.388
Not quite. I've spoken with Hutton.
there's been a development.

272
00:16:52.471 --> 00:16:53.389
What kind?

273
00:16:53.390 --> 00:16:57.186
Hutton told me the last person who held him
in captivity is a man known as the Simoon.

274
00:16:58.352 --> 00:17:00.980
- Get the hell out of there right now.
- Why? What do you know?

275
00:17:01.063 --> 00:17:02.940
The roads are swarming with patrols.

276
00:17:03.024 --> 00:17:05.026
which means the Simoon
is already on the scent.

277
00:17:05.109 --> 00:17:08.196
You need to get back to the airstrip
as fast as you can.

278
00:17:08.279 --> 00:17:09.697
We'll have the engines running.

279
00:17:09.780 --> 00:17:11.324
He's mobilised to find Hutton?

280
00:17:11.407 --> 00:17:14.452
And he'll burn the city to find him.
I'm bringing on extra men.

281
00:17:14.535 --> 00:17:16.621
We'll lock down the landing field.

282
00:17:16.704 --> 00:17:20.124
<i>You just get yourself there in one piece.
and I'll get us airborne.</i>

283
00:17:20.208 --> 00:17:21.584
We could be there in 30 minutes.

284
00:17:21.667 --> 00:17:24.962
Thirty minutes. Go. now. That gives you 15.

285
00:17:25.046 --> 00:17:27.340
Notify your men.
Tell them to expect a fight.

286
00:17:27.423 --> 00:17:31.177
It's gonna be a hell of a lot more difficult
getting out of town than it was getting in.

287
00:17:43.022 --> 00:17:44.690
- Denora Mejia?
- Yes?

288
00:17:44.774 --> 00:17:47.693
Agent Kevin Thompson. This is Agent Ritter.
Can we talk?

289
00:17:47.777 --> 00:17:49.654
It's about Elizabeth Keen.

290
00:17:51.572 --> 00:17:53.991
- I don't understand.
- But you're familiar with Reddington?

291
00:17:54.075 --> 00:17:56.452
- What does that have to do with...
- Have you heard of him?

292
00:17:56.535 --> 00:18:00.665
- Of course. He's a wanted fugitive.
- He's also Keen's father.

293
00:18:00.748 --> 00:18:01.832
Open it.

294
00:18:03.376 --> 00:18:07.797
That man is one of our agents.
He's staking out Keen's building.

295
00:18:07.880 --> 00:18:10.424
Four years ago. Reddington and Keen
went on the run together.

296
00:18:10.508 --> 00:18:15.471
- She was on the FBI's Most Wanted List.
- It says here her name is Masha Rostova.

297
00:18:15.554 --> 00:18:18.057
It also says she's the daughter
of a KGB agent.

298
00:18:18.140 --> 00:18:22.520
A notorious KGB agent
named Katarina Rostova.

299
00:18:22.603 --> 00:18:26.524
The agent out front. he's not looking
for Reddington. He's looking for her.

300
00:18:26.607 --> 00:18:29.151
As bad as he is. Rostova's worse.

301
00:18:29.235 --> 00:18:32.238
The child you're being asked to care for
is their granddaughter.

302
00:18:32.321 --> 00:18:37.368
They're in Keen's life. and if you
take this job. they'll be in yours as well.

303
00:18:37.451 --> 00:18:38.452
Right.

304
00:18:43.374 --> 00:18:47.420
I'm sorry.
I didn't mean to put anyone in danger.

305
00:18:48.629 --> 00:18:49.755
We'll make it. Dan.

306
00:18:49.839 --> 00:18:52.842
- Twenty minutes. and we're in the air.
- Yeah.

307
00:18:55.469 --> 00:18:57.805
All seems too familiar.

308
00:18:57.888 --> 00:19:01.225
- Long ride. hostile territory.
- Try and relax.

309
00:19:06.105 --> 00:19:10.234
I can't go back. Harold.
Not another hole in the ground.

310
00:19:10.318 --> 00:19:12.028
You're not going back.

311
00:19:12.111 --> 00:19:15.573
Yeah. well. this guy. the Simoon...

312
00:19:17.241 --> 00:19:23.205
if he comes after us.
maybe he can take you this time instead.

313
00:19:29.628 --> 00:19:33.007
You answered the phone.
so you're still alive. Where are you?

314
00:19:33.090 --> 00:19:35.634
We're approaching the checkpoint. Hang on.

315
00:19:44.393 --> 00:19:45.393
Hi. how are you?

316
00:19:46.854 --> 00:19:48.272
That's for both vehicles.

317
00:19:53.194 --> 00:19:54.195
You're together?

318
00:19:54.695 --> 00:19:56.530
Yes. and in a hurry.

319
00:19:57.198 --> 00:19:58.198
I don't like this.

320
00:19:58.240 --> 00:19:59.742
What's wrong?

321
00:19:59.825 --> 00:20:02.661
The policeman at the checkpoint.
he's carrying an HK416.

322
00:20:02.745 --> 00:20:05.331
<i>That's pretty new. And expensive.</i>

323
00:20:05.414 --> 00:20:08.667
- Too expensive for police.
- Harold. you need to get out of there now.

324
00:20:10.461 --> 00:20:12.380
- We got a problem.
<i>- Harold.</i>

325
00:20:12.463 --> 00:20:13.589
<i>Harold. talk to me.</i>

326
00:20:13.672 --> 00:20:16.133
- What happened?
- Get the Post Office on the phone.

327
00:20:17.510 --> 00:20:18.510
Harold?

328
00:20:27.561 --> 00:20:30.981
Tell them I work for
the United States government. The FBI.

329
00:20:31.065 --> 00:20:34.860
- We're here on official business.
- They know who you are. Harold.

330
00:20:36.320 --> 00:20:39.365
- How could they possibly know that?
- Because I told them.

331
00:20:45.079 --> 00:20:48.040
Looks like the Simoon
wants a word with you after all.

332
00:20:55.756 --> 00:20:58.801
- Anything?
- Nothing. But Aram's on with Reddington now.

333
00:20:58.884 --> 00:21:00.052
Got eyes on the checkpoint.

334
00:21:00.136 --> 00:21:03.556
<i>The last thing I heard was men
yelling in Farsi. and lots of it.</i>

335
00:21:03.639 --> 00:21:05.766
And that was 13 minutes ago.

336
00:21:05.850 --> 00:21:09.061
And if Harold was taken.
they may have put him in another vehicle.

337
00:21:09.145 --> 00:21:12.314
This is about the SIPRNet cable.
Daniel Hutton.

338
00:21:12.398 --> 00:21:13.649
Got it.

339
00:21:13.732 --> 00:21:15.818
Looks like they shoved him
into a blue sedan.

340
00:21:15.901 --> 00:21:18.571
Tracking from there. they headed northwest.

341
00:21:18.654 --> 00:21:22.741
Made their way to what looks like some kind
of old palace or estate outside Zahedan.

342
00:21:22.825 --> 00:21:24.368
We should call the State Department.

343
00:21:24.452 --> 00:21:27.746
- No. there's no time for that.
- They can start back-channel negotiations.

344
00:21:27.830 --> 00:21:30.040
<i>- I can do better.</i>
- Better than the State Department?

345
00:21:30.124 --> 00:21:32.585
Way better. And more importantly. faster.

346
00:21:32.668 --> 00:21:35.379
We have one chance to get Harold out alive.

347
00:21:35.463 --> 00:21:37.339
<i>so listen carefully.</i>

348
00:21:41.093 --> 00:21:44.430
How quickly fates change.

349
00:21:44.513 --> 00:21:48.434
- Isn't that right. Harold?
- What have you done?

350
00:21:48.517 --> 00:21:50.769
What I had to do to survive.

351
00:21:50.853 --> 00:21:55.566
Do you know how many different groups
held me over the years?

352
00:21:55.649 --> 00:21:58.360
The Kurds. the Iranians.

353
00:21:58.444 --> 00:22:00.446
Couldn't keep track after a while.

354
00:22:00.529 --> 00:22:03.032
Tell me. how easy was it to sell me out?

355
00:22:04.909 --> 00:22:08.037
- I never did that.
- You left me for dead

356
00:22:08.120 --> 00:22:11.373
because I found out you were
illegally funding those same Kurds.

357
00:22:11.457 --> 00:22:13.393
- That is not what happened.
- Because I blew the whistle.

358
00:22:13.417 --> 00:22:15.211
I had no idea we were gonna be ambushed.

359
00:22:15.294 --> 00:22:19.840
I heard you got the Navy Cross
for your bravery that day.

360
00:22:23.511 --> 00:22:25.638
But we know what really happened. don't we?

361
00:22:27.056 --> 00:22:29.558
This is Minesweeper One.
Lieutenant Harold Cooper.

362
00:22:29.642 --> 00:22:30.726
We are under attack.

363
00:22:31.727 --> 00:22:32.895
Hold on. Hutton. Hold on!

364
00:22:45.824 --> 00:22:50.287
But we weren't ambushed. were we?

365
00:22:50.371 --> 00:22:54.250
Your Kurdish pals came for me. not you.

366
00:22:55.751 --> 00:22:58.546
Get your hands off me! Harold!

367
00:23:02.925 --> 00:23:04.510
Cooper!

368
00:23:06.595 --> 00:23:10.975
Cooper! Cooper! Cooper!

369
00:23:19.858 --> 00:23:21.277
<i>They traded me.</i>

370
00:23:21.360 --> 00:23:27.032
Sold me to their enemies to fund their war.

371
00:23:27.116 --> 00:23:31.036
Everyone may think
that you would never leave a brother to die.

372
00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:33.205
but I know you'd never think twice.

373
00:23:33.289 --> 00:23:34.748
You can believe what you want.

374
00:23:35.708 --> 00:23:39.128
But I didn't plan the ambush.
and I wanted to go after you.

375
00:23:39.211 --> 00:23:40.671
Then why didn't you?

376
00:23:42.256 --> 00:23:44.049
- Was the ambush your idea?
- Mind your tone.

377
00:23:44.133 --> 00:23:45.843
Was Hutton captured to keep our secret?

378
00:23:45.926 --> 00:23:48.762
- He threatened to expose the mission.
- Get me back to Kuwait.

379
00:23:48.846 --> 00:23:52.766
Lieutenant Hutton was executed
by Kurdish rebels an hour ago.

380
00:23:58.355 --> 00:24:00.899
You survived an ambush.

381
00:24:00.983 --> 00:24:03.110
Fought valiantly.

382
00:24:03.193 --> 00:24:06.697
I'm going to recommend you
for the Navy Cross.

383
00:24:06.780 --> 00:24:10.451
That'll put you on the fast track. Harold.
Any job you want.

384
00:24:11.577 --> 00:24:14.830
Or you can raise a stink
and throw it all away.

385
00:24:14.913 --> 00:24:19.084
Either way. Hutton's still gonna be dead
and the cash flow continues.

386
00:24:19.168 --> 00:24:20.336
You had him executed.

387
00:24:20.419 --> 00:24:22.004
I followed orders.

388
00:24:24.423 --> 00:24:29.136
And if you're as smart as I think you are.
you will too.

389
00:24:30.888 --> 00:24:35.184
You were a traitor treated like a patriot.

390
00:24:35.267 --> 00:24:39.063
I was a patriot treated like a traitor.

391
00:24:40.606 --> 00:24:44.234
So that's what I became.

392
00:24:47.780 --> 00:24:51.116
It's you. You're the Simoon.

393
00:24:53.577 --> 00:24:55.204
Pleasure to meet you.

394
00:25:06.048 --> 00:25:09.009
- Do you know how to get to the White House?
- Sure.

395
00:25:09.093 --> 00:25:11.261
Spend a lot of money.

396
00:25:11.345 --> 00:25:13.681
Good to know Reddington
hasn't lost his sense of humour.

397
00:25:13.764 --> 00:25:15.683
- I'm Ressler.
- Campbell.

398
00:25:15.766 --> 00:25:19.478
- You know what we're supposed to do now?
- Yeah. Find the Dungeon Master.

399
00:25:33.450 --> 00:25:36.829
- Didn't you see the sign?
- Yeah. It said "open."

400
00:25:36.912 --> 00:25:39.331
- Well. we're not.
- Well. you are to us.

401
00:25:39.415 --> 00:25:40.833
Mr Homan said so.

402
00:25:46.839 --> 00:25:48.090
What the hell is this thing?

403
00:25:48.173 --> 00:25:50.634
It's not a PlayStation. pal.
Let's see the case.

404
00:25:55.222 --> 00:25:56.515
Two hundred thousand.

405
00:25:56.598 --> 00:26:00.102
And a set of coordinates. Mr Homan
said you'd know what to do with them.

406
00:26:00.185 --> 00:26:03.647
I do. Okay.

407
00:26:03.731 --> 00:26:05.858
Let's get the party started.

408
00:26:05.941 --> 00:26:08.277
I know what to do. Thank you very much.

409
00:26:19.079 --> 00:26:22.374
- What did we just pay for?
- No idea.

410
00:26:22.458 --> 00:26:25.669
And with Reddington. it's pointless to ask.

411
00:26:25.753 --> 00:26:28.881
So you work for him? Reddington?

412
00:26:28.964 --> 00:26:31.091
No. but he certainly thinks so.

413
00:26:32.634 --> 00:26:34.762
Yeah. It's done. Whatever it is.

414
00:26:34.845 --> 00:26:37.389
Splendid. Please thank Francesca for me.

415
00:26:37.473 --> 00:26:39.975
And trust that as far as
Harold is concerned.

416
00:26:40.058 --> 00:26:43.771
we are now in the gifted hands of a master.

417
00:26:43.854 --> 00:26:45.773
Time to storm the castle.

418
00:26:45.856 --> 00:26:48.192
It's a heavily armed compound.
There's only five of us.

419
00:26:48.275 --> 00:26:51.612
You're right. Even the Magnificent Seven
had seven.

420
00:26:51.695 --> 00:26:54.114
Slim chance of survival.

421
00:26:54.198 --> 00:26:57.242
Impossible odds. This will be fun.

422
00:27:01.955 --> 00:27:06.835
How could you do it?
The intel you gave Iran cost people's lives.

423
00:27:06.919 --> 00:27:09.046
I held out for years.

424
00:27:10.422 --> 00:27:15.219
Through beatings. in solitary. in cages.

425
00:27:16.720 --> 00:27:21.141
And I realised no one was coming.

426
00:27:23.143 --> 00:27:24.520
How could I do it?

427
00:27:28.816 --> 00:27:29.983
Harold...

428
00:27:31.777 --> 00:27:33.111
how could you?

429
00:27:33.195 --> 00:27:36.323
- You gave them access to naval intelligence.
- I did.

430
00:27:36.406 --> 00:27:39.827
Then they upgraded the network.
and I got shut out.

431
00:27:39.910 --> 00:27:43.664
After that. I interpreted data.
It was easy when I knew the players.

432
00:27:43.747 --> 00:27:47.417
That gave me value.
But now the only player I know is you.

433
00:27:47.501 --> 00:27:49.002
which is why you're here.

434
00:27:49.086 --> 00:27:50.629
I won't cooperate with them.

435
00:27:50.712 --> 00:27:53.841
- Because it's the wrong thing to do.
- The wrong thing.

436
00:27:55.175 --> 00:27:57.344
You certainly know all about that.

437
00:28:00.013 --> 00:28:01.932
By text. Not by phone.

438
00:28:02.015 --> 00:28:03.308
She quit via text.

439
00:28:03.392 --> 00:28:04.768
That's unbelievable.

440
00:28:04.852 --> 00:28:06.311
<i>I know. I thought she was perfect.</i>

441
00:28:06.395 --> 00:28:08.397
- What are you gonna do?
<i>- That's why I'm calling.</i>

442
00:28:08.480 --> 00:28:11.483
I am stuck at work
and Agnes is gonna be home soon.

443
00:28:11.567 --> 00:28:14.278
- I'm happy to help.
<i>- I'm so sorry about this.</i>

444
00:28:14.361 --> 00:28:16.697
Don't be silly.
I'd love to look after Agnes.

445
00:28:16.780 --> 00:28:17.865
<i>Really? Are you sure?</i>

446
00:28:17.948 --> 00:28:19.992
Of course. Take your time.

447
00:28:20.075 --> 00:28:23.912
The longer you stay at the office.
the more time I'll have to spoil her rotten.

448
00:28:23.996 --> 00:28:26.456
Thank you. You're a lifesaver.
I don't know what happened.

449
00:28:26.540 --> 00:28:28.375
<i>Don't beat yourself up.</i>

450
00:28:28.458 --> 00:28:30.669
Sometimes people just aren't
who they seem to be.

451
00:28:33.505 --> 00:28:35.215
No way we are getting in there.

452
00:28:35.299 --> 00:28:36.592
Where's your faith?

453
00:28:36.675 --> 00:28:38.802
Left my faith on the jet.
Let's go back and get it.

454
00:28:38.886 --> 00:28:41.722
- We breach in two minutes.
- Raymond. even with help...

455
00:28:41.805 --> 00:28:45.100
- It will be a bloodbath.
- Yes. but not our blood.

456
00:28:45.183 --> 00:28:49.730
So many of my prisoners. during torture.
they break down.

457
00:28:49.813 --> 00:28:51.440
Beg for mercy.

458
00:28:51.523 --> 00:28:54.067
But not you. Right. Harold?

459
00:28:54.151 --> 00:28:59.281
Remember those cages I said they kept me in
those first few years?

460
00:29:03.911 --> 00:29:06.038
You're in one.

461
00:29:06.121 --> 00:29:09.166
I'll check back on you in a few decades.

462
00:29:09.249 --> 00:29:11.793
For what it's worth. Dan...

463
00:29:14.254 --> 00:29:15.631
I am sorry.

464
00:29:38.946 --> 00:29:40.989
- Twenty seconds.
- This is a death sentence.

465
00:29:41.073 --> 00:29:42.991
Farhad. you and your men to the south.

466
00:29:43.075 --> 00:29:45.869
- Dembe. you and I to the north.
- They will kill us all.

467
00:29:45.953 --> 00:29:47.037
Ready on your go.

468
00:29:47.120 --> 00:29:50.958
- We are not ready. I am not.
- Ten. nine. eight...

469
00:29:51.041 --> 00:29:54.002
- What the hell?
- Here we go.

470
00:29:58.757 --> 00:30:02.386
I won a rather high-stakes game
of Magic: The Gathering recently.

471
00:30:02.469 --> 00:30:04.221
and I've called in my chits.

472
00:30:11.353 --> 00:30:12.896
Wait. listen to this.

473
00:30:12.980 --> 00:30:13.981
Listen.

474
00:30:22.364 --> 00:30:24.366
That's our cue. fellas. Let's go.

475
00:31:48.492 --> 00:31:50.285
Not another step.

476
00:31:51.536 --> 00:31:54.247
Looks like you have
better friends than I did.

477
00:31:54.331 --> 00:31:56.625
At least they tried to save you.

478
00:31:59.711 --> 00:32:01.963
Raymond. I'm out of ammo.

479
00:32:09.596 --> 00:32:11.890
Come out! Come out now.

480
00:32:16.812 --> 00:32:18.146
You're outgunned!

481
00:32:18.230 --> 00:32:19.815
Show us your hands!

482
00:32:24.653 --> 00:32:25.654
Red!

483
00:32:30.534 --> 00:32:32.077
What took you so long?

484
00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:33.954
It's over. Dan.

485
00:32:34.037 --> 00:32:35.038
No.

486
00:32:35.122 --> 00:32:37.666
I won't let you leave me behind again.

487
00:32:37.749 --> 00:32:39.793
If I can't trade you to the Iranians.

488
00:32:39.876 --> 00:32:42.129
I'll trade you to your own people
for a way out.

489
00:32:59.521 --> 00:33:02.149
Harold! Help me!

490
00:33:02.232 --> 00:33:05.402
Please. help me. Harold. Please.

491
00:33:06.820 --> 00:33:09.072
Harold. please.

492
00:33:09.948 --> 00:33:11.199
Cooper!

493
00:33:13.493 --> 00:33:14.493
Cooper!

494
00:33:14.536 --> 00:33:16.288
Cooper!

495
00:33:16.371 --> 00:33:17.998
Cooper!

496
00:33:34.014 --> 00:33:35.223
I'm sorry.

497
00:33:35.307 --> 00:33:39.561
Harold. you should've learned
your lesson the first time.

498
00:33:44.274 --> 00:33:45.525
Harold. are you okay?

499
00:33:52.115 --> 00:33:53.325
I couldn't leave him again.

500
00:33:53.408 --> 00:33:55.744
We have to go.
He isn't your burden anymore.

501
00:33:56.870 --> 00:33:57.828
Isn't he?

502
00:33:57.829 --> 00:34:00.540
What is it you need. Harold?
A reminder that you're a good man?

503
00:34:00.624 --> 00:34:03.585
A moral man? You didn't need
to save Daniel Hutton to know that.

504
00:34:03.668 --> 00:34:05.212
You just needed to look in a mirror.

505
00:34:05.295 --> 00:34:07.547
What I did to him
has followed me half my life.

506
00:34:07.631 --> 00:34:08.757
It's time to let it go.

507
00:34:08.840 --> 00:34:10.550
Now. come on. We need to move.

508
00:34:33.990 --> 00:34:35.909
You did what you thought was right.

509
00:34:37.327 --> 00:34:41.164
Put your safety on the line
for a man you thought was your friend.

510
00:34:41.248 --> 00:34:43.959
He betrayed you. and now he's dead.

511
00:34:44.042 --> 00:34:46.461
Your secret is safe.

512
00:34:46.544 --> 00:34:51.466
If there was ever a reason to celebrate.
the Simoon is finished.

513
00:34:51.549 --> 00:34:54.552
You helped yourself and your country.

514
00:34:54.636 --> 00:34:58.098
Close the book. Raise a glass.

515
00:35:04.062 --> 00:35:05.313
How do you do it?

516
00:35:05.397 --> 00:35:08.942
Wake up each morning content to live a lie?

517
00:35:09.025 --> 00:35:13.196
How do you put on a face for the world?

518
00:35:13.280 --> 00:35:14.864
I don't live a lie.

519
00:35:17.033 --> 00:35:22.580
I may once have had another identity.
but that identity no longer exists.

520
00:35:22.664 --> 00:35:25.959
I am exactly who I am.

521
00:35:27.002 --> 00:35:28.628
And I can assure you.

522
00:35:28.712 --> 00:35:30.922
I'm a far more interesting
Raymond Reddington

523
00:35:31.006 --> 00:35:32.924
than Raymond Reddington ever was.

524
00:35:33.008 --> 00:35:35.218
And what about Ilya Koslov?

525
00:35:35.302 --> 00:35:40.348
I've always believed who you are
should define you. not who you were.

526
00:35:41.683 --> 00:35:46.354
And I don't know anyone
that should be more at peace

527
00:35:46.438 --> 00:35:49.316
with who they are than you.

528
00:35:49.399 --> 00:35:53.445
Whatever decisions you make going forward...

529
00:35:56.573 --> 00:35:58.783
I hope they grant you that peace.

530
00:36:07.625 --> 00:36:11.087
Do you like contests?
Because I love contests.

531
00:36:11.171 --> 00:36:15.759
- What kind of contest?
- I was thinking a drawing contest.

532
00:36:15.842 --> 00:36:22.307
I know you like princesses.
so I got a princess colouring book.

533
00:36:22.390 --> 00:36:27.645
I bet you can't colour a whole page in.
say. five minutes.

534
00:36:27.729 --> 00:36:31.191
Do you think you can?
Then that's the contest.

535
00:36:31.274 --> 00:36:33.360
Take this book and these pencils

536
00:36:33.443 --> 00:36:38.281
and go into your room. In five minutes.
I'll come in and see if you finished. okay?

537
00:36:54.672 --> 00:36:57.967
Mr Reddington called in a drone strike
from a gaming store?

538
00:36:58.051 --> 00:37:01.179
I don't know how he did it.
just that it saved my life.

539
00:37:01.262 --> 00:37:04.724
Why were you there in the first place?
I mean. why go with Reddington?

540
00:37:04.808 --> 00:37:08.103
Other than that he can call in
a drone strike from a gaming store.

541
00:37:08.186 --> 00:37:11.189
I went with Reddington
because we have no authority in Iran.

542
00:37:11.272 --> 00:37:13.817
And the reason I went was simple.

543
00:37:13.900 --> 00:37:16.861
Thirty years ago. I thought a soldier
in my unit had been killed.

544
00:37:16.945 --> 00:37:17.945
Daniel Hutton.

545
00:37:17.987 --> 00:37:20.156
The SIPRNet cable
told you he was still alive.

546
00:37:20.240 --> 00:37:21.156
Right.

547
00:37:21.157 --> 00:37:25.912
I went to try and bring him home.
and in the process. he died.

548
00:37:25.995 --> 00:37:28.289
That's awful. Were you two close?

549
00:37:28.373 --> 00:37:30.041
We were. once.

550
00:37:30.125 --> 00:37:33.670
In many ways. he was instrumental
in shaping the person I am today.

551
00:37:38.174 --> 00:37:41.594
Is your mind made up about what you're
gonna tell her about Reddington's identity?

552
00:37:41.678 --> 00:37:42.971
It is.

553
00:37:45.181 --> 00:37:47.642
It's made up about a lot of things.

554
00:37:47.725 --> 00:37:51.563
Well. isn't this like
finding four peas in a pod?

555
00:37:51.646 --> 00:37:55.483
Is there a snowball's chance in hell
I'm gonna like anything y'all have to say?

556
00:37:55.567 --> 00:37:58.570
I'd say definitely not.

557
00:38:00.738 --> 00:38:03.199
Harold. to the Scotch.

558
00:38:09.664 --> 00:38:12.542
You said you wanted
to talk about Reddington.

559
00:38:12.625 --> 00:38:14.836
so talk.

560
00:38:16.254 --> 00:38:17.422
Reddington is...

561
00:38:20.049 --> 00:38:22.051
He's not the person you think he is.

562
00:38:24.512 --> 00:38:28.808
Okay. I'll bite. Who is he?

563
00:38:32.437 --> 00:38:35.565
He's a much better person
than I gave him credit for.

564
00:38:36.608 --> 00:38:38.651
I. on the other hand. am not.

565
00:38:39.944 --> 00:38:42.280
Harold. you're not making any sense.

566
00:38:48.411 --> 00:38:50.121
What is that?

567
00:38:50.205 --> 00:38:52.790
A truth I should have told a long time ago.

568
00:39:14.687 --> 00:39:17.482
Okay. five minutes are up!

569
00:39:17.565 --> 00:39:19.984
Ready or not. here I come!

570
00:39:30.995 --> 00:39:33.873
You're giving the Navy Cross to the Simoon?

571
00:39:33.957 --> 00:39:35.416
I'm putting it where it belongs.

572
00:39:36.543 --> 00:39:37.919
He was a brave man.

573
00:39:39.587 --> 00:39:41.381
I was a coward.

574
00:39:41.464 --> 00:39:45.468
He refused to follow an illegal order.
I insisted on carrying it out.

575
00:39:45.552 --> 00:39:48.054
I knew the payments weren't authorised.

576
00:39:48.137 --> 00:39:51.307
that someone up the chain of command
was breaking the rules.

577
00:39:51.391 --> 00:39:56.229
They were higher on that chain than I was.
so I didn't ask any questions.

578
00:39:56.312 --> 00:39:58.314
And I didn't stand with Hutton when he did.

579
00:39:59.649 --> 00:40:01.025
I left him behind.

580
00:40:01.109 --> 00:40:03.069
You were told he was dead.

581
00:40:04.153 --> 00:40:07.949
I should've gone back to look for him.
found him.

582
00:40:09.242 --> 00:40:13.663
But I didn't.
And that turned him into the Simoon.

583
00:40:16.457 --> 00:40:19.377
The Daniel Hutton I left behind that day
deserves this.

584
00:40:19.460 --> 00:40:22.630
If it had been you.
you never would have betrayed your country.

585
00:40:22.714 --> 00:40:24.757
He tried speaking truth to power.

586
00:40:24.841 --> 00:40:29.637
and the powerful punished him for it
and rewarded me for letting them.

587
00:40:32.348 --> 00:40:34.309
I gave Panabaker the flash drive.

588
00:40:36.269 --> 00:40:38.187
That won't wipe his slate clean.

589
00:40:38.271 --> 00:40:44.152
I didn't do it for him. I did it for me.
And I have you to thank for that.

590
00:40:44.235 --> 00:40:48.615
You told me that people should be defined
by who they are. not by who they were.

591
00:40:49.907 --> 00:40:54.871
The cover-up. the medal.
they represent who I was.

592
00:40:54.954 --> 00:40:56.998
A man willing to look the other way.

593
00:40:57.081 --> 00:41:04.005
Who I am. who I hope to be. is someone
who takes responsibility for his actions.

594
00:41:04.088 --> 00:41:05.965
So you're a truth-teller now.

595
00:41:07.592 --> 00:41:10.094
Did you tell Panabaker the truth about me?

596
00:41:11.346 --> 00:41:12.346
I did.

597
00:41:14.891 --> 00:41:16.976
I told her your true identity.

598
00:41:17.060 --> 00:41:20.021
Who you are. not who you were.

599
00:41:22.023 --> 00:41:24.108
I told her you're Raymond Reddington.

600
00:41:28.154 --> 00:41:32.450
I love it. More importantly. Agnes loves it.

601
00:41:32.533 --> 00:41:35.411
- We had fun.
- You really saved me today.

602
00:41:35.495 --> 00:41:40.291
- I told you before. I'm happy to help.
- I still can't believe Denora bailed on me.

603
00:41:40.375 --> 00:41:41.709
You'll find the right person.

604
00:41:41.793 --> 00:41:43.836
But until you do.
you can always count on me.

605
00:41:43.920 --> 00:41:46.589
I think I'll be counting on you a lot.

606
00:41:51.386 --> 00:41:55.098
- Fun times with the urchin?
- Productive times.

607
00:41:59.686 --> 00:42:00.895
What am I looking for?

608
00:42:00.978 --> 00:42:03.356
Second photo. top of the page.

609
00:42:06.067 --> 00:42:09.445
Ilya Koslov. Who's he?

610
00:42:09.529 --> 00:42:12.532
The one person who can tell me
what I need to know.
